\f1\b\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 \expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
User interface
\b0 \cf3 . Almost all operating systems have a 
\b \cf6 user interface \cf3 (
\fs24 \cf6 UI
\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 )
\b0 \cf3 . This interface can take several forms. One is a 
\b \cf6 command-line interface \cf3 (
\fs24 \cf6 CLI
\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 )
\b0 \cf3 , which uses text commands and a method for entering them (say, a keyboard for typing in commands in a specific format with specific options). Another is a 
\b \cf6 batch interface
\b0 \cf3 , in which commands and directives to control those commands are entered into files, and those files are executed. Most commonly, a 
\b \cf6 graphical user interface \cf3 (
\fs24 \cf6 GUI
\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 ) 
\b0 \cf3 is used. 
\f2\fs24 \cf4 \

\f1\b\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 Program execution
\b0 \cf3 . The system must be able to load a program into memory and to run that program. The program must be able to end its execution, either normally or abnormally (indicating error). 
\f2\fs24 \cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl260\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b \cf3 I/O 
\fs26\fsmilli13333 operations
\b0 . A running program may require 
\fs24 I/O
\fs26\fsmilli13333 , which may involve a file or an 
\fs24 I/O 
\fs26\fsmilli13333 device. For efficiency and protection, users usually cannot control 
\fs24 I/O 
\fs26\fsmilli13333 devices directly. 
\f2\fs24 \cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 File-system manipulation
\b0 \cf3 . Programs need to create and delete files and directories by name, search for a given file, and list file information. Finally, some operating systems include permissions management to allow or deny access to files or directories based on file ownership. 
\f2\fs24 \cf4 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl300\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f1\b\fs26\fsmilli13333 \cf3 \dn3 Communications
\b0 . There are many circumstances in which one process needs to exchange information with another process. Such communication may occur between processes that are executing on the same computer or between processes that are executing on different computer systems tied together by a computer network. Communications may be implemented via 
\b \cf6 shared memory
\b0 \cf3 , in which two or more processes read and write to a shared section of memory, or 
\b \cf6 message passing
\b0 \cf3 , in which packets of information in predefined formats are moved between processes by the operating system. 
